               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1315" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1315" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1315" type="surname" value="PECK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1315" type="given" value="MICHAEL HORDEN"></interp>MICHAEL HORDEN PECK.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a dry-salter, at Southwark-bridge. The prisoner was in my service about four months—on the 16th Oct. I gave him fifteen sovereigns, a half-sovereign, and 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in silver, to take to Spa-road, Bermondsey, to Mrs. Julia Adams, a manufacturing chemist—Mr. Barber manages her business for her—I have done business for them for years—the prisoner did not come back—I did not see him again till the Tuesday fort-night—I charged him with this—he made no reply—it was his duty to come back, and he did not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALDWIN.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you a manufacturing chemist? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, a dry-salter—I supply muriate of lime and oil of vitriol—I had connexion in business about two months ago with a man named Bateman—I know Marshall-street—I have no place of business there, Bateman had—when I did business with him there was an illicit still there—I had nothing to do with it, I had no benefit from it—I used sometimes to get sweet spirits and allum.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1316" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1316" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1316" type="surname" value="BARRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1316" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY BARRY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 171.) I took the prisoner at the corner of King David-lane, Ratcliff. On the 2nd Nov. there had been hand-bills published, and a reward of two guineas offered—I said I took him for robbing Mr. Peek, in Southwark-bridge-road—he said he did not know Mr. Peck, and his name was not Dixon, it was Brown—I said, "I know you are the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220222"></xptr>
               <p>man, I must take you over the water"—I took him to Mr. Peck's—he iden<lb></lb>tified him as George Dixon, and the man who has stolen the money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1317" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1317" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1317" type="surname" value="BARBER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1317" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY BARBER.</persName>
                  </hi> I manage the business fro Mrs. Julia Adams, of Spa-road. On 16th Oct. I did not receive fifteen sovereigns and other money, brought by the prisoner—Mrs. Adams lives there, but does not interfere in the business at all.</p>
